summary:
Ibudilast has theoretical potential as an anti-inflammatory agent in multiple sclerosis due to its mechanism of action involving suppression of CNS inflammation through phosphodiesterase inhibition. However, there are currently no clinical trial results demonstrating improved outcomes such as reduced relapses, slowed disability progression, or symptom relief in patients with MS; therefore, it lacks proven clinical efficacy for managing the condition.

\boxed{\text{No}}

The summary focuses only on clinically significant findings related directly to treatment effects in MS—excluding mechanisms without direct relevance—and clearly states both the lack of supporting evidence and absence of established benefit despite plausible biological activity.

